Extract only composers and works that the page says will actually be performed. Return composer/work pairs, not separate lists. Use the standard English title of the complete composition for work.title. A movement or excerpt belongs to that canonical complete composition; use its standard English name in programme_label. Do not copy source-language work titles into either field merely because that is how the page presents them. Preserve the relevant original wording in evidence instead.

Before proposing a new composer, run:
  uv run python -m agent_utils.concert_catalog find-composer --name "NAME"

For each resolved composer, search works with:
  uv run python -m agent_utils.concert_catalog find-works --composer-id ID --query "TITLE"

If matching remains unclear, inspect every work by that composer with:
  uv run python -m agent_utils.concert_catalog list-works --composer-id ID

These commands are read-only and return JSON. Reuse existing IDs whenever the identity is defensible. Do not guess. If any composer or work is ambiguous, return status ambiguous and explain why; the harness will make no catalogue writes. If the page is reachable but no specific programme is published, return no_program. If it cannot be reached, return page_unavailable.

For complete results, provide concise evidence copied or paraphrased from the programme and the URL where it was found. Use full canonical composer names and standard English canonical work titles for proposed new entities. Set existing IDs to null only after using the lookup commands and finding no match.
